My latest newsletter features an interview with photojournalist Gabriele Galimberti, who took the photos for Balenciaga’s pulled holiday campaign featuring toddlers and these bear bags. Prior to speaking with him, I researched his work and found his Toy Stories series of kids with their toys charming and compelling in a way photography seldom is. His series on Americans and guns called Ameriguns is done in a similar style, equally memorable, and even more urgent. I found it terribly sad that his vision for this series — 15 years in the making — had been applied by Balenciaga to advertising that was poorly conceived and even more poorly received. Gabriele’s experience is a window into the compromises artists might make to take on lucrative commercial work with partners like Balenciaga. Read the full piece at the link in bio. #balenciaga #fashion #photography #fashionphotography

Anna has published 395 print Vogue covers during her nearly 35-year tenure. Out of those, 50 have featured “nepo babies.” For the purposes of this exercise, I defined nepo baby as someone with prominent parents, though other cover subjects I didn’t count had parents in the film business (working as script supervisors or something like that). So this might even be a conservative tally. Does 13 percent feel high to you? It did to me even knowing how much privilege and Vogue have gone together over the course of Anna’s career. #vogue #nepobaby #nepotism #annawintour #fashion #magazine #magazinecover

These are just a few facts I learned about Anna when reporting my book ANNA: The Biography. Everyone I interviewed told me they were amazed at how much she gets done in a day. After her work day, she’s often going to an event or dinner, then goes home and finishes work by around 11 before going to bed and doing it all again — so she’s sleeping like 6 hours a night. And no, she doesn’t sleep in the Tuesday morning after the Met Gala. #annawintour #vogue #voguemagazine #routine #morningroutine #fashion #metgala #annathebiography

This clip is an outtake from Vogue documentary The September Issue by the brilliant RJ Cutler which came out in 2009. Not only was the late great André Leon Talley on point with his concerns about office germs, he also says something I heard from sources again and again when reporting ANNA: The Biography — that being a cultural sponge was seen as crucial to working at Vogue under Anna. She expected her team to see art exhibits, plays, movies — anything to curate their taste and sharpen their eye. With the dawn of digital media, when editors and writers are expected to be at their computers or on their phones posting constantly, this became much harder to do. While I wish this approach was still possible, I suspect it’s part of a bygone era now. Anna Wintour’s legacy will likely be in part how she pushed the worlds of fashion and entertainment together. Under Anna, celebrities became de facto Vogue cover subjects, which spilled over to magazines more broadly. It also influenced the fashion industry at large, which started using celebrities in ad campaigns and as red carpet billboards, all of it coming to a head at the Met Gala. Vogue’s 1989 cover with Madonna helps explain how it all got started. Learn more in my book ANNA: The Biography, linked in bio. #annathebiography #madonna #annawintour #vogue #voguecover #fashion #celebrity #metgala #magazine

The @modelallianceny and @saraziff have been working with NY lawmakers to pass a bill that would regulate modeling agencies.

The Fashion Workers Act would provide models and content creators with protections that Ziff sees as basic, essential, and maddeningly overdue. However, as I exclusively report in my newsletter Back Row, a group of six agencies calling itself the Coalition for Fairness in Fashion has banded together to stop the current bill from passing. 

“There is zero financial transparency, and there’s also no obligation for the agency to act even in your interests,” said Ziff. “That’s some Britney Spears shit. When we’ve been meeting with lawmakers, they’re shocked. They’ve never heard of that before in any other industry.”

These financial arrangements, Ziff argues, beget sexual exploitation and human trafficking. “Just think about the most prominent people in the #MeToo movement, whether it was Bill Cosby or Jeffrey Epstein or Harvey Weinstein,” she said. “The common denominator is they were all preying on girls who wanted to work as models.”

New York Fashion Week just wrapped, and I discuss the confusion around its purpose in 2024 in my latest newsletter: 

“Who is it for in 2023? The industry, or people who can amplify the industry online, who are not necessarily the same crowd? What is it for? To showcase great fashion and present new ideas for how we dress? Or to get social media impressions? After so much agreement during the pandemic that fashion was white-washed and thin-centric, can fashion week actually be diverse?

“These are the same questions people have been asking in recent years about Hollywood award shows. Who are they for? The industry or consumers, who don’t see many of the winning films? In 2022, the movie that won Best Picture, Coda, had been seen by just 4 percent of general entertainment industry consumers, according to a poll conducted in the lead-up to the Oscars. And what are award shows for? To honor the best for a niche consumer audience of film buffs, or to promote the industry to a mass audience? And is the industry following through on promises to honor diverse talent, or falling back on its old ways?”

Sustainable fashion journalist and author Alden Wicker of @ecocultcom and I collaborated on a newsletter about the realities of becoming a fashion journalist in the 2020s. 

Every month seems to bring more bad news for media as digital outlets — once thought to be the industry’s savior — struggle. So far in November, Condé Nast announced it was cutting 5 percent of its workforce, Jezebel shut down, and we learned Vice was eliminating dozens of jobs. These kinds of cuts will only continue as Google, Meta, and Amazon continue hoovering up the majority of digital advertising revenue, and publishers adjust to tech companies directing traffic elsewhere. A report from Challenger, Gray & Christmas showed that through October, more than 19,000 job cuts had been announced by media in 2023, while 2022 saw 3,000 cut in the same period.

So, what can aspiring fashion journalists do? Alden and I share our thoughts at the link in bio.

In thinking about how to sum up the year for fashion, I kept coming back to Deluxe, by @danathomasparis. Published in 2007, the book remains a must-read.

Thomas laid out the economics of the luxury fashion industry, which evolved from small companies that focused on the highest quality product to huge conglomerates, like Kering and LVMH, focused on making as much money as possible. “Disposable income has risen significantly in industrialized nations in the last thirty years,” Thomas wrote in Deluxe. “Both men and women have put off getting married until later in life, freeing them to spend more on themselves. The average consumer is also far more educated and well traveled than a generation ago and has developed a taste for the finer things in life.”
